<kml>

<concept name=Take-Apart><system-documentation name=Take-Apart>
<superconcept name=Destroy>

<definition>

  Take apart, i.e. disassemble, an object.  
  The object is <conceptref name=Destroy>'ed, 
  but the parts continue to exist as separate entities.

</definition>

<requiredslotlist>

  <slotdescription name=object>
     The object that's taken apart.
  </slotdescription>

</requiredslotlist>

<primaryslotlist>

  <slotdescription name=agent>
    the entity responsible for the disassembly.

  <slotdescription name=instrument>
    the thing that was used to take apart the object.
  </slotdescription>

  <slotdescription name=by-means-of>
    the event that caused the disassembly.
  </slotdescription>

</primaryslotlist>

<examplesentencelist>

  <examplesentence>
    <text>John disassembled the engine.</text>
    <slotdescription name=object>the engine</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=agent>John</slotdescription>
  </examplesentence>

  <examplesentence>
    <text>A screwdriver was used to take apart the table. </text>
    <slotdescription name=object>the table</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=instrument>a screwdriver</slotdescription>
  </examplesentence>

  <examplesentence>
    <text>The earthquake shook apart the condo. </text>
    <slotdescription name=object>the condo</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=by-means-of>the earthquake</slotdescription>
  </examplesentence>
  <comment>

    Alternatively, the disassembly of the condo was by-means-of a
    shaking which was <slot>caused-by</slot> the earthquake.

  </comment>

</examplesentencelist>

<neighborlist>

  <neighbor name=Divide>
     Take-Apart disassembles an object, whereas Divide
     cuts an object into two pieces.

  </neighbor>

</neighborlist>

</kml>


